SIMPLE: summons
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Summons
<hw>Sum"mons</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Summonses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>somouns</ets>,
OF. <ets>sumunse</ets>, <ets>semonse</ets>, <ets>semonce</ets>, F.
<ets>semonce</ets>, <ets>semondre</ets> to summon, OF. p. p.
<ets>semons</ets>. See <er>Summon</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of summoning; a call by authority, or by the command of a
superior, to appear at a place named, or to attend to some
duty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Special <qex>summonses</qex> by the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>summons</qex> . . . unfit either to dispute or
disobey.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Fell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sent to summon the seditious, and to offer pardon; but neither
<qex>summons</qex> nor pardon was regarded.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A warning or citation to appear in
court; a written notification signed by the proper officer, to be served
on a person, warning him to appear in court at a day specified, to
answer to the plaintiff, testify as a witness, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A demand to surrender.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Summons</ent>⟦br⟧

